[2]
Date: Wed 10 Feb 2010
Source: Brisbane Times online [edited]
<http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/travel/travel-news/measles-scare-at-tourist-mecca-20100210-nr0l.html>


A foreign tourist with a case of measles has triggered an infectious
disease alert in the holiday playground of the Whitsundays.
Queensland Health this morning [10 Feb 2010] issued a measles
outbreak warning for the region after the man tested positive. He had
been staying at Airlie Beach between 30 Jan and 4 Feb 2010. Tropical
Regional Services Medical Officer Dr Steven Donohue said the man had
brought the illness from overseas, and authorities feared it could
easily spread. "Although the patient didn't get measles in Australia,
he would have been highly infectious while in the Airlie Beach
region," Dr Donohue said. "We're concerned about the possibility of
the measles virus spreading into the local community and elsewhere in
Queensland due to the large number of travellers and visitors to the area."

Dr Donohue said the traveller had been taken part in a range of
holiday activities around Airlie Beach, and Queensland Health
officers were now retracing his footsteps to identify anyone who may
have come into contact with him. "Queensland Health will continue to
actively investigate all cases and take steps to prevent further transmission."

Measles is spread in tiny droplets through coughing and spluttering,
and can be active for several hours in the environment, experts say.
While most people in developed countries are immunised against it as
children through the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine (MMR), babies
under 12 months of age and anyone who has not been vaccinated are at
risk of falling seriously ill. Complications from the disease can
include pneumonia and encephalitis (inflammation of the brain).
"Measles can be very distressing for those affected ... (and) can be
a severe illness even in otherwise healthy adolescents and young
adults," Dr Donohue said. Symptoms include fever, lethargy, a runny
nose, moist cough, sore and red eyes, and a blotchy red rash. Dr
Donohue said symptoms usually start around 10 days after contact with
an infected person.

[Byline: Christine Kellett]

