******
[3]
Date: Thu 4 Feb 2010
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/02/04/2810215.htm>


A measles alert has been issued after someone arrived in Darwin
infected with measles. The Northern Territory Centre for Disease
Control has issued a measles alert after confirming an infectious
person passed through Darwin last week [i.e. presumably last week of
January 2010].

The centre says the person flew to Darwin from Ho Chi Minh City in
Viet Nam on Jetstar flight JQ74 on Australia Day [26 Jan 2010].
Passengers left on the same flight bound for Sydney at 7 am.
Passengers sitting near the infected person have already been
contacted by health authorities. "However, there is still a small
risk that other passengers and visitors to the airport may have been
exposed," said the director of the Centre for Disease Control, Dr Vicki Krause.

"Measles is a very contagious viral illness that is spread between
people through coughing and sneezing," she said. "It can affect all
ages, but children under 12 months and anyone not immune are at much
greater risk. To be immune to measles, you need to have either had
measles or had 2 doses of measles vaccine." She said typical symptoms
include fever, cough, runny nose and sore eyes, followed by a red
blotchy rash appearing 3 to 4 days later.

The measles alert applies until 19 Feb 2010.

[Byline: Emma Masters]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Queensland is particularly vulnerable to introduced infections by
virtue of its role as a popular tourist destination. Measles is
highly contagious and can be spread from an infected person before
symptoms develop. The risk is highest in flights originating from or
picking up passengers in countries where measles is common and not
controlled effectively by vaccination.

In this case, the origin of the infected tourist in Queensland is not
stated. The ABC report suggests that a person on a flight from Viet
Nam may have been responsible for introducing the virus. It is
unclear if the Darwin/Sydney airplane exposure alert refers to the
same case as mentioned in the Queensland alert. Clarification of
this from knowledgeable sources would be greatly appreciated. Measles
can be transmitted by an infected person from 4 days prior to the
onset of the rash to 4 days after the rash erupts.

The 1st sign of measles is usually a high fever, which begins about
10 to 12 days after exposure to the virus, and lasts 4 to 7 days. A
runny nose, a cough, red and watery eyes, and small white spots
inside the cheeks can develop in the initial stage. After several
days, a rash erupts, usually on the face and upper neck. Over about 3
days, the rash spreads, eventually reaching the hands and feet. The
rash lasts for 5 to 6 days and then fades. On average, the rash
occurs 14 days after exposure to the virus (within a range of 7 to 18 days).

A map of Queensland showing the location of the Whitsundays can be
accessed at <http://www.about-australia.com/maps/queensland/>, and
the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Australia is available
at: <http://healthmap.org/r/00cS>. - Mods.CP/MPP]
